One of the DevOps engineers was trying to deploy a python app on Kubernetes cluster. Unfortunately, due to some mis-configuration, the application is not coming up. Please take a look into it and fix the issues. Application should be accessible on the specified nodePort.
The deployment name is python-deployment-devops, its using poroko/flask-demo-app image. The deployment and service of this app is already deployed.
nodePort should be 32345 and targetPort should be python flask app's default port.

Note: The kubectl utility on the jump-host has been configured to work with the Kubernetes cluster.
solution
1. Check the deployment and service
kubectl get deploy
kubectl get svc

Then inspect them:

kubectl describe deployment python-deployment-devops
kubectl describe svc python-service-devops

If you don't know the service name:

kubectl get svc
The service is already using NodePort 32345, but I can already see two problems:

Deployment image is incorrect
Current: poroko/flask-app-demo
Required: poroko/flask-demo-app
Service targetPort is incorrect
Current: 8080
Should be 5000 (the Flask app's default port)

The deployment has 0 available pods, so let's also check why the pod isn't starting.

Step 1: Check the pod
kubectl get pods

Then describe it:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

If the image cannot be pulled, you'll see ImagePullBackOff or ErrImagePull.

Step 2: Fix the deployment image
kubectl set image deployment/python-deployment-devops \
python-container-devops=poroko/flask-demo-app

Wait for rollout:

kubectl rollout status deployment/python-deployment-devops
Step 3: Fix the Service

Patch the target port to 5000:

kubectl patch svc python-service-devops -p \
'{"spec":{"ports":[{"port":8080,"targetPort":5000,"nodePort":32345}]}}'

or edit it:

kubectl edit svc python-service-devops

and make it:

ports:
- port: 8080
  targetPort: 5000
  nodePort: 32345
Step 4: Verify
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
kubectl get endpoints python-service-devops

The endpoints should no longer be empty.

Before doing anything else, run:

kubectl get pods

and paste the output. That will confirm whether the issue is only the wrong image or if there's another pod startup error.

