The problem is confirmed.

The image name is wrong.

Current (invalid):

poroko/flask-app-demo

Required:

poroko/flask-demo-app
1. Fix the deployment image
kubectl set image deployment/python-deployment-devops \
python-container-devops=poroko/flask-demo-app

Wait for the rollout:

kubectl rollout status deployment/python-deployment-devops
2. Fix the Service targetPort

The service currently has:

Port:        8080
TargetPort:  8080
NodePort:    32345

The Flask app listens on 5000, so change only the targetPort:

kubectl patch svc python-service-devops \
-p '{"spec":{"ports":[{"port":8080,"targetPort":5000,"nodePort":32345}]}}'
3. Verify
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc
kubectl get endpoints python-service-devops

The pod should become Running, and the endpoints should no longer be empty.

If the kubectl set image command fails because the image poroko/flask-demo-app doesn't exist either, run:

kubectl describe deployment python-deployment-devops

or

kubectl rollout status deployment/python-deployment-devops

and share the output. Some KodeKloud labs intentionally use a different image name than the prompt, and we'll identify the correct one.

